segments.text: We sat there and Don Spirison, who is now my partner, who was running cardiovascular systems at Amnion at that time, we had to face up to the fact that going forward, our product, we had a low technology product, and our competitors, we felt that there would be a technology evolution in that market.
that it would eventually go, say, from centrifugation to separate the blood to maybe some membrane technology.
We didn't feel that our company had the resident R&D capability to advance that product to the next generation.
So it was looking at that, looking at our inability to finance an acquisition after really actually having a hard time even finding something worth buying,
We felt pretty much that maybe we should take the bird in the hand instead of the two in the bush.
In retrospect, it was still probably the right decision to make.
Is that a typical pattern, not the pattern of that particular company, but the pattern of venture capital?
What I guess I'd like to know a little bit, I find this really fascinating, one of the things I'd like to know, I guess, is
how the company itself evaluates what it's going to do, on what basis it makes its decisions.
Because my preconceived notion was that venture capital was sort of an upfront thing.
Once it gets its money, it's out of it.
It's not really interested in managing companies.
If we have to manage companies, we know we're in trouble, because we know the management that we selected is incapable.
We don't want to manage companies on a day-to-day basis.
It is the board, when you're talking about buying or selling or doing something major, that is a board decision, just as it's a board decision at IBM or Mitchell Energy.
And the venture capitalists usually have fairly good representation on the board of directors.
So we are involved in that decision.
Our particular venture organization here has been more of an active manager than most venture organizations because
We have been the founders of many of these companies.
And number one and number two, the personalities of the three of us partners now are more, we're more active than passive.
We don't manage where we don't want to be managed.
But when it comes to things like in that particular case, even though Don is now my partner in Venture Capitalist, I was very active in identifying
with Abbott Laboratories through contacts, the product line that we were looking to acquire.
I had some contacts that provided us the banking contacts that we looked at trying to finance it.
And it was, in fact, our relationship with the first Boston corporation who acted as investment bankers to Cove Laboratories.
They actually called us about our interest in whether the company would be interested in selling.
So venture capitalists don't want to be involved long-term in companies.
They don't want to be involved in day-to-day management.
But in the short term, in all things that are of strategic value or matters of liquidity to their investment, they'll take an active involvement in it.
How does the staff research, I assume the staff research is done, to buttress these sorts of decisions?
How is that developed?
And within the venture capital company?
Well, the three of us, we virtually live and breathe in the health care industry.
We've had people, for example, my partner's father had a heart condition about a year ago.
He's out in California.
And he's in the hospital.
Michael went out there.
And Michael, for two years, Michael
within our group had been our person who was looking at investments in interventional cardiology.
He is more knowledgeable about every type of catheter, laser, roto-ablater to fight plaque and arteries than probably many physicians.
And he's, because we're constantly looking for new technologies and products, he's probably more aware of new products than many physicians.
And in that particular case,

He recommended to the cardiologist in Southern California that they should talk to John Simpson up in San Francisco, who has had just gotten approval with the FDA to do, I think, an atherectomy procedure with one of his rotoablation devices.
And so we're pretty knowledgeable about what's going on in the marketplace.
And we're pretty knowledgeable about values of companies.
And we feel that we're

we think we're pretty qualified to make decisions when you want, you know, to make an acquisition, when you want to grow the company more, when you don't think you can grow it as much as it's, you know, to the rate of growth that you might be able to realize now if you sold it.
So we take, in some cases, maybe even more so than management, who are focused on their single company and less aware of what all the other companies and what the competitors.
Yeah, we're real industry-oriented.
We go to
And we go to health care meetings and medical conferences constantly to keep attuned to what's going on in the marketplace.
And so what you're saying, by way of sort of summary, is that without that expertise, this company in any way wouldn't really be able to function the way it does.
I think so.
I think the difference between if you say what makes someone a venture capital investor versus not being a venture capital investor in the
You know, the industry adages that we're active versus passive, or we add value as opposed to, you know, just being a passive investor.
And how do you add value?
You add value by being involved in the broader industry, by being able to make decisions, bring contacts to the company that any individual company or its management group might not have itself.
Access technology.
We are constantly getting proposals.
We have contacts at universities all across the United States.
If we're trying to build one of our own companies, we have a company right now that's an animal veterinary pharmaceutical company.
And it has a great product, one of the most elegant, one of the most desirable products that will ever be on the market, I believe.

Nonetheless, it's just one product, and if they want to build around that product, they either have to do it themselves, which, you know, what's the capability of one or two scientists to add more products when there are, you know, thousands every year trying to develop new ones of which only a few succeed, versus us who are constantly seeing deals and proposals and know that so-and-so is working on such-and-such at such-and-such university, and we can help
those companies either access other technologies or know when not to develop one themselves because someone else is doing it.
So were we to put this in the context of, say, a military operation, you feed into the strategic principles by providing key and timely intelligence of where the world is going and what
what's going to be striking.
If I could remember that exact statement, I would use it because that is, in essence, what we try to do.
And sometimes we're capable of doing it, sometimes we're not.
But that, in fact, is what we're trying to do.
Okay.
I'll do it.

About the same time that we had launched cardiovascular systems independently and were starting to work with the University of Texas for the creation of LifeCell, as Dominic might have mentioned, Dominic had been at Baylor, and he had been interested in creating a new company.
Mitchell had been talking to Baylor for years about having a presence out in the woodland.
Dominic had been courted by people in Vancouver, Canada, and I think Temple University in Philadelphia had courted him.
Arnold Beckman had courted him to move out to Irvine, California.
And some people had talked about creating an institute of this or professorship of that.

And the bottom line out of all that was that, and I think an important element of this process was that Baylor agreed in many ways to support Dominic and to support George Mitchell's vision to create the Center for Biotechnology out here in the Woodlands, which I do believe has helped them attract
scientists that they might not have otherwise attracted.
A good example is Bill Benedict, who came from the Doheny Eye Institute at the University of Southern California, a world-class scientist.
He has just flat-out told me that he would never have come to Baylor and come to Texas if it hadn't been for Baylor's Center for Biotechnology in the woodlands.
And did you have any participation in the development of that center?

No, that was really done through Mitchell and the Woodlands Corporation, but it tied in a lot to Houston Biotechnology, which was Dominic's company, which we became the lead venture capital behind in 1985-86.
We brought in someone, acted as interim president for that company, and they've raised a lot of money.

And now they, along with Argus Pharmaceuticals, are really the first two private biotechnology companies in Texas who have filed investigational new drug applications with the Food and Drug Administration to begin human clinical trials, which for us in our portfolio, we break down our portfolio
of companies and that biotechnology to us, we have a more limited definition of biotechnology than I think most people in Texas have.
We limit it to those companies that are involved in the fields of cell and molecular biology.
And so this is recombinant DNA, monoclonal antibodies and that.
Then we have what we just consider our medical biomedical technology, which are devices, instrumentation, things like that.
And then there's health care services.

In our portfolio of, say, 17, 18 companies, we really have three pure biotechnology companies, two that are biotechnology-related, and then the balance are medical device and instrumentation, excepting one, which is a service company.
There are six of those companies, I think, that are here in the woodlands.
and all three of the pure biotech companies.
And the significance of those companies is that we almost should scratch the buzzword biotechnology.
They're pharmaceutical companies.
Pharmaceuticals are the bread and butter of the health care industry in terms of that's where the big bucks are.
It costs a lot to develop them, costs a lot to get them approved.
When you sell them, you generate a lot of revenues, and they have high profit margins.
And it's big business.
Unless you use the context of Fortune 100 as being your definition, there aren't many small pharmaceutical companies.
You're either big, or you're not in the business, or you're going to get absorbed by someone.
And this is exciting, because the
The biotechnology industry really evolved on the coast in the late 70s and early 80s.

And I've always marked the 70s and early 80s as nationally being the science generation for biotechnology in the United States, where they were developing these tools of cell fusion and recombinant DNA.
And then in 1986, the first couple, I think there actually were
actually four bioengineered products approved by the Food and Drug Administration in 86.
So I kind of marked, you know, the 86 as the beginning of the product generation nationally in biotechnology.
Here in Texas, we really look at the 80s as being the science generation for biotechnology here, and it was mostly in the academic laboratories.

And the 90s where we're real excited about this year is that, you know, in those three pure biotech companies, Houston Biotechnology, Argus Pharmaceuticals, and Zonagen, they were consumed with research and development throughout the period of time they existed in the 80s.
However, 1990 and 1991, each one of those three companies will be going into clinical trials with us.
So now,
that really marks the beginning of the product generation for biotechnology in Texas.
And in that case, and each of those three companies is here in the Woodlands, Houston Biotechnology has a monoclonal antibody-based product that would prevent secondary cataracts from forming.
And that, we estimate, is a worldwide market of at least $250 to $300 million.
Argus Pharmaceutical has
not one, but three products that we think they'll be in clinical trials within the next two years.

But the initial product that they filed their IND with about a month ago is a formulation of a topical antifungal that now with our new formulation has indications systemically as both an antifungal and an antiviral.
And because this won't
be published before all this probably evolves along in the press.

This drug has been tested at MD Anderson at the National Cancer Institute of the National Institute of Health in a very prominent laboratory there and has shown the greatest potency against the AIDS virus than any other drug, including AZT.
And the significance is that not only does it prevent replication of the virus, but also it has shown an ability to in vitro kill HIV-infected cells, but not be toxic at all to healthy cells.
And at the FDA, they've just been pushing us, literally,
to get this in clinical trials.
So we're very excited about that product.
And there's still a lot of you never know.
In clinical trials, it may pan out that it's not effective.
But right now, all the indications look very positive.
Then the third company, Zonagen, that's also out of Baylor College of Medicine.
And we're proud of that.
That's kind of our Texas product.
network.
We created the company.
I'm the chairman of the board of that company.
We're the lead investor, but then our other two major investors, one is Ross Perot, and the third is a venture fund called Triad that's headed by Lloyd Benson III.
You've got Mitchell, Perot, and Benson, three big names in Texas, backing that.
It's one of the most
elegant, marvelous technology.
It is a immunocontraceptive vaccine that has been funded by Dr. Bonnie Dunbar at Baylor College of Medicine for many years by the Mellon Foundation.
She's been involved with the World Population Council, the World Health Organization to develop a contraceptive vaccine to prevent pregnancy in mammals.
In her case, her grants are aimed towards a human contraceptive vaccine for
third world countries like China and India.
Now, when we, when I came across this at Baylor, I thought, you know, geez, from the moral, ethical, regulatory implications of human contraception, I'm not, I don't think I'm going to be interested.
However, has anybody considered the commercialization of this product in the animal marketplace?
And so we took it upon ourselves to evaluate that.
And what we found, we have found out is that, uh,
there's a 500 to $600 million worldwide market, uh, for female dogs and cats to have a vaccine as opposed to having a surgical intervention.
And, uh, it's, uh, it's, uh, the way that the product works, uh, and those, uh, parents side effects, uh, just a marvelous technology.
So incidentally, Donna has been writing a history of,
Veterinary medicine in Texas.
Is that right?
Is that right?
Well, I think that's just going to be a major, major, major product.
And we've been talking with Merck and a number of other pharmaceutical companies.
They're really in the veterinary pharmaceutical area.
We've had, in fact, the Merck people were in here two days in this very conference room about a year ago.
And Merck has really got some smart people.
And they...

indicated to us that if you could just conceive it on the board today, even that which has not yet been invented or discovered, they can conceive of only five products that would be $100 million-plus products in animal health.
One happens to be a product, the largest happens to be a product that they do have.
It's called ivermectin, which is
I for almost any type of fungal about anything that's wrong with an animal.
They give it ivermectin.
It's and that's about a $600 million product.
But then they said that the second largest product, if they existed, would either be a contraceptive vaccine or a flea vaccine, none of which exists today.
And then the other two one they indicated would be a heart drug, which I thought was a little biased towards, you know, they're

Yeah, they don't have it, but what a lot of these companies will do is they'll develop a human product, and then if they think the animal market's big enough, they'll adjust their program to modify their human product to be an animal product, and they have a human heart drug that I think they're planning on introducing in the animal marketplace, and there's one other one which escapes me right now.
So if this works and field clinical trials, we hope to start
You know, by the middle of next year, you know, that'll tell.
But our market research has indicated, you know, an 85, 90-plus percent acceptance rate of this product in the marketplace.
And that company is here in the woodlands.
So those three, Houston Biotechnology, Argus, Zonagen, are the three biotech companies in the woodlands.
We have two device instrumentation companies.
Excuse me, one, LifeCell Corporation was that first one launched out of UT, and that has probably the most esoteric technology that we came across.
They have a process of ultra-rapid cooling followed by molecular distillation drying, which it's a very high-tech way of
Freeze drying, right.
It will preserve biological samples, if you will.

And the, you know, the breakthrough here is that, you know, the problem when you freeze something is you'll either have damage due to ice crystal formation, or what you can do to mitigate that is you can subject the sample to
a cryoprotectant.
Typical ones are DMSO, dimethyl sulfoxide, or some other things, and they're essentially antifreeze.

And they will displace the water in the biological specimen so that you're not getting ice crystal formation, but of course these are chemicals and they're very toxic, so you're chemically altering the sample.
What the life cell process does is, again, it uses no cryoprotectant, but it
And by this ultra-rapid cooling, the water at the molecular level will form almost an amorphous or glass-like phase.
But then by subjecting it immediately then to this vacuum that's the equivalent to an outer space vacuum, it causes these glass-like water molecules to sublimate the tissue.
So what you have in the end is something that is
structurally and chemically intact.
And they were just, in fact, mentioned a big article in the Wall Street Journal about a month ago.
They've received a number of grants from the federal government, and that particular one was from, I think, the Navy to preserve red blood cells like that.
Uh, and that company, uh, we we founded that company and that was the first out of U. T. And this year they'll do about $1,000,000 in sales, uh, on their equipment side of their business.
The things like red blood cells.
Uh, you know, they're also working on preserving skin, a number of other things like that.
You know, those are more like the drugs.
They're going to be longer term in their development and application.
Then the other device company that we have here, Optex Biomedical, had as its origin Texas A&M, although we were not involved in the formation of that company.
There were four young scientists, three of them who were at A&M that had developed some optic fiber technology at A&M.
And they, in fact, had licensed it from the university and gotten some funding from a group of doctors here in Houston initially.
a few hundred thousand dollars.
Then we came along, I guess, in about 1987 or 88, and we led a financing that included a number of large institutional investors.
And what they're developing is what we believe will be the world's first fiber optic-based real-time blood gas monitoring system.
And we believe that on the device side, this is perhaps the hottest market.
In fact, when we had an annual meeting, one of our annual meetings, I think it was two years ago, we had it down at the medical center.
And Dr. DeBakey was kind enough to take us into his auditorium and visit with us for about 40 minutes.
And it's interesting because
Someone asked him, well, how are we going to stop rising health care costs?
And he says, well, that's really very simple.
Of course, everybody's, how can it be simple?
Everybody's trying to figure it out.
And he was being sarcastic, partly.
But he said, there's a very simple answer to stop rising health care costs.
That is, you stop all research and development.
And he explains, he says, well, if we don't develop any new technology, then doctors won't find new ways to charge patients money.
And the point he was making was, he's part sarcastic, but he was also saying that, you know, if you're a cardiologist and you're a good cardiologist, you could diagnose
heart disease 20 years ago before they had this or they had that.
If you're a good doctor now, basically what you're doing is if you can show anybody how to use this equipment, someone off the street could be able to diagnose heart disease.
And there is some, and people are using it because of protection of liability.

You know, if you're an anesthesiologist and you don't want to get sued because you lose someone, then you've got to use anything that anybody is using that would seemingly protect you and your information, you know, they're going to use.
So there are more and more ways to charge patients.
So he was being, you know, sarcastic, but he was partially being true, being honest too.
But then having said that,
Someone asked him then, what would be the next greatest breakthrough that you would hope for in the clinic?
And he, without hesitating and having no idea what any of our companies were involved with, really, he said real-time blood gas monitoring.
And so and we estimate at bare minimum that that, you know, medical devices, if you're addressing 50 to 100 million dollar market, that's very large.
And it's only usually these pharmaceutical products that address these, you know, multi hundred million dollar markets.
But we estimate at and analysts around the around the globe estimate at least 300 million dollars and some as large as a billion dollars for that particular marketplace.
And they
are expected to launch their product next year.
It has been FDA approved, but it has not been engineered down to its final ergonomic design.
So we expect them to launch that next year.
And that's a company, for example, that they are projecting that within three or four years they might have as many as 400 or 500 employees.
here in the woodlands.
So that's almost Houston's medical version of compact computer.
Well, that's exciting.
Yeah, yeah.
It's exciting.
What is your, and I'm not sure we're ready for this question yet, but one thing that occurs to me so far is that Mitchell and the woodlands provided assistance in launching these things.
And right now, you basically are spun off and are now
separate independent venture capital company, and that you are here is almost coincidental or incidental to what's happening in and around the Woodlands.
The Woodlands is complimentary and supplements what you're doing, but right now you're doing other things.
In other words, the medical complex is not.
No, and interestingly is that, again, way back when I was able to convince
the Mitchell organization, that we have enough infrastructure or resource base here in Houston and in Texas to make this successful.
And the woodlands, because I was going to use it as a tool to help me be successful in this, and the woodlands would benefit from it.
But I convinced from, I certainly convinced Bud Clark, George,
said he was convinced.

He probably still hoped otherwise, but everybody accepted the fact that every company that we invest in can't be in the Woodlands, practically speaking, unless you can't exist on doing only a company whenever it happens to be one that you can locate here.
So really, going back as far as probably 1986 or 87, they had agreed basically that I think they accepted the fact that
I might know what I'm doing and that I have made investments outside of the woodlands.
In fact, if we go back, you know, even starting in 86, and a good year for us was where we'll do three companies.
And it has just historically fallen that one of those will end up in the woodlands, one of them will be Texas non-woodlands, and one of them will be outside of Texas.
that prescription has worked well for us and has been accepted by them.
The interesting thing, in 1988-89, we became independent of Mitchell, but in all candor, his vision has not been lost by me.
Number one is that his vision is an accurate vision.
Number two, I'm very loyal to him.
And number three, it has been a formula that has produced success for us.
So even though our financial base is larger now, includes more than Mitchell, we operate exactly the way we operated in 1986, 1987.
Does he still participate in any way or capital?
He has, you know, Mitchell, and again, I just can't tell you how big of a fan I am of George Mitchell because...
Certainly, going back to our Mitchell years, it was his company, it was his money, it was his initial vision.
He could have suggested anything.
And one of the things people asked me about was, well, do you ever get pressure from George to do this deal and that deal, or a friend, blah, blah, blah?
And it has been perhaps because he himself is an entrepreneur and understands the process.
He has never pushed us on doing anything.
In fact, the contrary.
Whenever, quote, one of George's alleged friends had a deal, those would be the times that he would call me saying, well, yes, I do or I don't know so-and-so very well.
And this is what he's going to talk to you about, but I don't have any opinion about it.
You just make your own judgment.
Always supported me to let us make our own judgments.
I spent, I remember in those early years in particular, we'd always prepare.
And we'd do so much homework on these things.
We'd be down there.
And we were also out of time.
And one of the reasons that I pushed us
separating from Mitchell was you got to go back into the 86 and 87.
Here we were.
People were surely going into Mitchell's office saying, we want to drill more wells.
Well, money's tight.
We're not going to be able to do so much this year.
Surely people were going in there saying, we want to pave new roads, and we want to do this in the woodlands.
And surely they were getting, well, money's tight.
We're going to maybe have to defer some of those to next year.
He, even when oil was $9 a barrel, I went in there and I asked him for money to do this deal or that deal.
30 seconds later, I have it.
He was so incredibly supportive of this thing, even during the worst of Mitchell's economic times.
But nonetheless, and even though he was supportive, I personally felt that that must be very awkward for him.
The presidents of

Oil and gas divisions are probably wondering why Marty Sutter, who's investing in these things that no one knows anything, couldn't understand them and had no interest in understanding, why is George giving them money?
So I told him, and I think I convinced him, that this is my vision.
Maybe your vision was initially that this would just support
the real estate development of the woodlands, and maybe my vision might have been this.

But what's happened is that our visions have blended to being one and the same, and I'm committed to this strategy, to this operating mode, and it really doesn't matter whether you're the only pocket to back it or I get other pockets to back it.
I'm going to do the same old, same old.
and we have in fact followed that.
In addition to his support now, we have funding from, we're the first venture fund that the University of Texas invested in out of its endowment.
We're the first venture fund that the Meadows Foundation in Dallas invested in.
We have the first Boston Corporation, Minnesota Mutual Life Insurance Company, the Delta Airlines Pension Fund, first city bank in town.
the TISO organization in Switzerland.
These people are all investing in this vision of taking this medical research that we have in Texas and commercializing it and, in fact, have recognized that the companies that

Going forward, if we were in a horse race and we wanted to bet on, I tell you, I'd take these five or six we have here in the woodlands over the rest of them because they're origins from strong academic laboratories here out of the Texas Medical Center that we have been able from day one not to just get satisfied with management but go out and pick who we felt were the absolutely best people to run these companies.
We have
fostered the continued growth of that science through participating in research and development grants at the academic institution with the academic scientists there.
And we have been able to bring substantial, sophisticated capital resources to these companies.
How do you relate to the Houston Advanced Research Center, HARC, now in terms of this kind of development?
There's less a direct relationship today other than Dr. Porter, who's the president of HARC, is the chairman of my scientific advisory committee.
Nonetheless, as an institution, HARC has...
Really, it's still too young in its life cycle to be a producer of technology.
It has developed an infrastructure to do so.
But number one, because initially our focus was on the life sciences, and there is not.
There wasn't much interaction, although
We have always anticipated that, prospectively, there will be some.
And in fact, we have organized what's called the Research Forest Technology Association, which includes about 13 companies now, of which Mitchell is not involved.
We felt that this was something that we needed to not have Uncle George hand-holding us, that we needed to take the initiative amongst ourselves.
to form at our last breakfast.
And the presidents of those 13 organizations, we meet once a month and we discuss a variety of things.
And Dr. Porter did tell us at the last meeting that he was planning on developing a program more life sciences oriented.
So we think that either interventions off what they're doing today, and they have, they developed through the superconducting supercollider, they developed a magnetic resonance imaging magnet that
may have some commercial value, and out of their laser applications research center, they developed an intervention there that they think might have some clinical value.
We chose not to finance either one of those projects, but it was, and again, there's another example where George isn't pushing us on anything.
He's letting us make our best judgment.
In our particular case, us three partners have some
you know, some adverse feelings towards high-cost capital equipment ventures, and that's why we didn't participate in the magnet.
And on the laser side, we just fear that laser technology worldwide is advancing so rapidly that, in fact, the technology is probably advancing more rapidly than the clinical application.
And we could be wrong, but that just happens to be our feeling towards those two things.
So we didn't finance those, but we expect that they will be long-term a source of opportunities for us.
Do you have any direct involvement with the Woodlands Corporation in your company or on the board or anything like that?
None.
We are presently totally independent of them, although, again, it's now because we've got this
this critical mass of 13 companies.
I'm the chairman of the board of two of those companies, and we're clearly actively involved with all of them through the RFTA or what have you.
We work, in the case of Mike Richman, I interact a lot with Mike because, again, I'm going to be selfish in that I'm going to be primarily interested in the success of these companies.
And I have felt that the woodlands is a tool to help make them successful, the result of which will be strong and has been strong economic development of the woodlands.
But the woodlands corporation is, you know, real estate people may think differently than technology entrepreneurs.
So I think, and Michael Richman is,
Not your typical real estate person.
I think he shares the vision as well.

And he is someone that I can go to who will be who I'll say, well, Michael, uh, you know, what you need to consider is you need to consider, uh, uh, some type of development of a facility that can be shared by these companies for this purpose.
And.
whereas maybe the average real estate person might say, well, what revenues is it going to produce, how much is it going to cost type of thing.
Michael is going to be more inclined to understand the qualitative value of that in terms of,
helping these companies.
It doesn't matter how much it costs, if it helps or what the payback is.
It's not as if it's not a factor.
But more importantly, if it helps these companies be successful, it means that they stay here and they grow larger and produce more jobs or it helps attract other companies there.
then Michael is usually willing to listen to those recommendations or suggestions.
And because it's a little bit easier for me to explain those things to him than perhaps the single entrepreneur who's maybe just looking out for his company's own best interest.
So we communicate a lot in that fashion.

Maybe as sort of a concluding comment or anything you'd like to go on, fine, but would you comment, maybe now that you've reached this critical mass in terms of the biomedical community, what do you expect to happen over the next decade?
A lot has happened, but not for the last decade, clearly.
I think the biggest challenge that we're going to have, the good news is that we have some outstanding companies.
Some of these companies are going to grow up and be, to different degrees, success stories a la compact computer.
Some of these companies are going to grow up and be successful but be acquired.
and may or may not have a lasting impact on the woodlands in Texas.
And some of these companies, although we're almost more amazed and proud because we've had so few failures, but there will be failure.
If there isn't failure, then we haven't been taking enough risk.
And we believe that we have to be risk takers to hit home runs.
And so a lot of that will evolve in the future.
And to what degree, we're still not sure.
Right now, we are immensely positive about the success of these companies.
The good news is that we don't believe that the technology base, i.e., the academic
creation, the academic discovery process is going to go away.
I think we're, you know, we're going to, there's going to be challenges to continue to make sure federal grant money goes to all our fine academic institutions.
We believe that's going to continue to be there and hopefully grow stronger.
What we're going to get a net gain in is the fact is the, the management base, because just as when cardiovascular amnion cardiovascular systems amnion was sold,
That was, for the Woodlands, that was not so good because, you know, they then were not a permanent resident of the Woodlands.
But what it meant was the president of that company became my partner and is now working with me.
